The first Indian National Union session was held in Kolkata at Albert Hall from 28 to 30 December 1883.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hssXP1hBYscC&dq=national+conference+1883&pg=PA54|title=History of the Freedom Movement in India (1857-1947)|last=Sen|first=S. N.|date=1997|publisher=New Age International|isbn=9788122410495|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TI8GQioaoL4C&dq=national+conference+1883&pg=PT256|title=Land of Two Rivers: A History of Bengal from the Mahabharata to Mujib|last=Sengupta|first=Nitish|date=2011-07-19|publisher=Penguin UK|isbn=9788184755305|language=en}}</ref> It was prompted by Introduction of the Criminal Procedure Amendment Bill (1883–1884) or [[Ilbert Bill]]. Anandamohan Bose depicted this conference as the first stage towards the formation of a National Indian Parliament. The conference demanded introduction of representative assemblies for the advancement of the people of India.<ref>{{Cite news|date=2018-02-27|title=A divided electorate throws up a polarised mandate: Pranab Mukherjee|language=en-IN|work=The Hindu|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/resources/a-divided-electorate-throws-up-a-polarised-mandate-pranab-mukherjee/article22869084.ece|access-date=2020-08-01|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>
The second Indian National Union was also held in Kolkata from 25 to 27 December 1885. Along with the [[Indian National Association|Indian Association]], the [[National Mohammadan Association]] and the [[British Indian Association]] were also conveners of this meeting. On its last day, the second National Conference sent a message of goodwill to the [[Indian National Congress]].<ref name=":0" />

